"Very close to 160 million people are now working in the United States," Trump told a crowd of supporters in Milwaukee.
The Bureau of Labor Statistics tracks a range of data including jobs, unemployment and the number of people working.
When asked to back up the claim, Trump’s campaign pointed to data from the BLS’ Current Population Survey, also known as the household survey.
"Just to note, this is different from the number of jobs added (nonfarm payroll)," Trump aide Zach Parkinson said in an email.
But the number Trump cites to support that claim isn’t the only — or the best — way to analyze it.